🚧 Project 1: Production-Grade CI/CD Pipeline for a Backend Service
1. Problem Statement

You are working at a startup building a backend service that will power a customer-facing application (e.g., task management API).

The company is preparing for its first production release. Your responsibility is to:

Build a reliable, automated CI/CD pipeline
Ensure every code change is validated before deployment
Enable safe, repeatable deployments with rollback capability
Provide basic observability and operational readiness

⚠️ Reality check:
This system will be touched by multiple developers. Your pipeline must prevent bad code from reaching production.

2. Requirements
✅ Functional Requirements

You must build:

Application Layer
Backend service (FastAPI or similar)
PostgreSQL database
Health endpoints:
/health/live
/health/ready
CI Pipeline (Triggered on PR + main branch)

Pipeline MUST include:

Code Quality Stage
Linting (flake8 / ruff)
Formatting (black)
Pre-commit hooks (optional)
Fail pipeline if violated
Testing Stage
Unit tests (mandatory)
Integration tests (DB involved)
Minimum coverage threshold (you decide — justify it)
Security Checks
Dependency vulnerability scan (e.g., Trivy, Snyk, pip-audit)
Fail on critical vulnerabilities
Build Stage
Multi-stage Docker build
Image must be:
Small
Non-root user
Tagged properly
Artifact Management
Push Docker image to registry (Docker Hub or similar)
Versioning strategy (semantic versioning or commit SHA)
🚀 CD Pipeline (Triggered after successful CI on main)
Pull latest image from registry
Deploy to target environment
Run DB migrations (safe + idempotent)
Validate deployment using health checks
Auto rollback on failure
🔒 Secrets & Config Management
No secrets in code
Use environment variables or secret manager
Separate configs for:
dev
staging
prod
📊 Observability
Structured logging (JSON preferred)
Basic metrics (Prometheus format)
Expose /metrics
Log correlation (request ID)
🔁 Deployment Strategy
Must support:
Rolling update OR
Blue/Green (preferred if you can simulate)
Zero/near-zero downtime expected
3. Non-Functional Requirements (This is where most people fail)

You must define and meet:

Availability Target: e.g., 99.9%
Deployment Success Rate: > 95%
Pipeline Duration Target: < 10 minutes
Rollback Time: < 2 minutes
Cold Start Time: minimized
4. System Constraints
Single VM (e.g., EC2 or similar)
Docker-based deployment (NO Kubernetes)
Low traffic (but design should scale later)
Budget-conscious (no over-engineering)
5. Architecture Expectations (High-Level Only)

I expect you to think in terms of:

Separation of concerns:
CI system
Artifact registry
Runtime environment

Example flow (you refine this):

Developer → Git Push → CI Pipeline → Build & Test → Docker Registry →
CD Pipeline → VM Deployment (Docker Compose or similar)
You should justify:
Jenkins vs GitHub Actions
Why your deployment method is safe
6. Deliverables

You must produce:

Repository Structure
CI/CD Pipeline Configuration
Dockerfile (production-grade)
Docker Compose (for local + staging)
Deployment scripts
Rollback mechanism
README with architecture + decisions
Demo flow (what happens on commit?)
7. Evaluation Criteria (I will be strict here)

I will judge you on:

🧠 Engineering Thinking
Do you understand failure scenarios?
Do you design for rollback BEFORE deployment?
🔐 Security
Are secrets handled properly?
Are images hardened?
⚙️ Reliability
What happens if deployment fails halfway?
What if DB migration fails?
📦 Maintainability
Can another engineer understand your system in 10 minutes?
📉 Operational Readiness
Can I debug issues using your logs/metrics?
🧪 Before You Start — My Questions for You

Answer these before you design anything:

CI/CD Tool Choice
Jenkins or GitHub Actions?
Why? (Don’t say “easy to use”)
Deployment Strategy
How will you achieve zero downtime on a single VM?
Database Migration
What happens if a migration fails after deployment starts?
Rollback Plan
What exactly will you roll back?
Code? Container? Database?
Versioning Strategy
How will you tag Docker images?
Secrets Management
Where will secrets live in:
local
CI
production VM
